&gt; OK, a lot of talk is of some value, but action speaks 
&gt; much louder. In this case the action needed is an ANN 
&gt; that can be presented with a random sequence of binary 
&gt; patterns, and then repeats them back one at a time. 
&gt; It could be in reverse order, or in the order of 
&gt; presentation. Each pattern might be 16 bits, or maybe 
&gt; only 8 or 10. 

&gt; The model is a human who is told to dial a phone 
&gt; number, and then dials it. 

This is not the form of memory I&#39;m trying to develop. I&#39;ll try to 
explain. 
A human is very advanced form of intelligence and remembering 
a sequence if a very machine-like process. I don&#39;t think I&#39;m a 
very stupid human, and more than five or six ones and zero&#39;s in 
a row is not only very difficult to remember, ( I would have to 
explicitly apply heuristics like grouping and rhythm ), it&#39;s also 
totally meaningless. 
Like Ion said, doing a small part of a task is really really hard, 
but looking at the task as a whole starts to make sense. What 
do we need this sequence of bits for? 
If I were going to dial the phone number, ( because I have a 
terrible memory ) I would first find a way to record the number 
to a long term memory ( like pen and paper or palm pilot ) then 
use the phone and the paper together to make the call. 
these are learned behaviors in long term memory, but while 
the behavior of &#39;make the phone call&#39; is being carried out, there 
is short term memory of where the paper is. I never had to store 
any sequences of numbers to my own long term memory. 

Do you see the difference in the kind of memory I&#39;m describing? 
In the future, I think the integration of long term memory with 
short term memory will make for very powerful systems. I just 
don&#39;t think we fully understand short term memory yet. 

chad 

